#compdef logtalk_tester
# =============================================================================
# logtalk_tester — The canonical Logtalk test-runner shell script.
#                  Automates running unit tests written in Logtalk
#                  found in the current directory and recursively in
#                  sub-directories by scanning for `tester.lgt` /
#                  `tester.logtalk` source files.  Dispatches to ONE
#                  of 15 supported Prolog backends (B-Prolog, Ciao,
#                  CxProlog, ECLiPSe, GNU Prolog, JIProlog, XVM,
#                  SICStus, SWI-Prolog, SWI-Prolog-pack, Tau,
#                  Trealla, XSB, YAP) via the `-p` argument, runs
#                  Logtalk's `lgtunit` framework over the discovered
#                  test sets, collects results in seven possible
#                  output formats (default, TAP, xUnit, xUnit.NET v2,
#                  CTRF, SubUnit v1, SubUnit v2), and emits coverage
#                  reports in XML / Cobertura / lcov.  Returns
#                  non-zero exit code if any test set fails or errors
#                  out — making it suitable for CI integration with
#                  GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Travis CI, Jenkins.
#                  Used by every Logtalk project's continuous-
#                  integration pipeline.
#
# Author:  Paulo Moura (<pmoura@logtalk.org>) — Logtalk's sole
#          designer + lead implementer since 1998 (28 years of
#          continuous development); Carnegie Mellon University
#          Software Engineering Institute affiliate; one of the
#          most prolific declarative-programming researchers active.
# Source:  https://github.com/LogtalkDotOrg/logtalk3
# CLI:     scripts/logtalk_tester.sh (bash + POSIX getopts builtin)
#          (`while getopts "vzp:o:m:f:d:t:j:n:s:b:u:c:l:e:g:r:i:wh"`
#           — single-letter flag string passed to bash's POSIX
#           getopts shell builtin which iterates through `$@`,
#           validating that each `-flag` matches the registration
#           string and that `value:` flags have a value following.)
# Library: POSIX `getopts` shell builtin (IEEE Std 1003.1-2017)
#          (the OLDEST documented CLI parser pattern in the
#           taxonomy — predates clap/cobra/commander/argparse by
#           decades.  POSIX getopts was standardized in 1992 IEEE
#           Std 1003.2 (POSIX.2), but the underlying `getopt(3)` C
#           library function it wraps was written by AT&T's Henry
#           Spencer at Bell Labs in 1980-1981 and has been UNIX
#           canon ever since.)
# License: Apache-2.0
# Status:  Active — Logtalk 3.95 (latest as of June 2026); 483+
#          stars on LogtalkDotOrg/logtalk3; in continuous development
#          since 1998 (28 years).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 66TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its 66TH LANGUAGE — Logtalk.  Logtalk joins the corpus as a single-
# instance language (Logtalk=1) via its canonical `logtalk_tester.sh`
# bash + POSIX-getopts test-runner script.  Taxonomy now spans 272
# cross-language CLI library variants across 66 documented languages.
#
# Leaderboard unchanged: Rust=40 / Go=40 / TS-Node=40 (three-way tie
# at 40 preserved from R532).  Logtalk=1 (new — 66th language entry).
#
# This is the FIRST documented DECLARATIVE OBJECT-ORIENTED LOGIC
# PROGRAMMING language in the taxonomy.  Every other documented logic
# language (Prolog R???, Picat, BQN, Curry/PAKCS, Datalog) is either
# pure logic (Prolog) or constraint-logic (Picat).  Logtalk extends
# Prolog with classes, objects, categories, protocols, parametric
# objects, hierarchies, events, multi-threading, and reflection —
# while remaining 100% backward-compatible with ISO Prolog.  No other
# documented language is "Smalltalk-meets-Prolog."
#
# Pattern: R530/R531/R532 were three leader bumps completing the
# TUI-WIDGET-FRAMEWORK triple across Rust/Go/TS-Node.  R533 (THIS)
# returns to NEW LANGUAGE — Logtalk as 66th.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS LOGTALK AND WHY IS IT THE 66TH LANGUAGE?
#
# Logtalk (https://logtalk.org, https://github.com/LogtalkDotOrg/
# logtalk3, 483+ stars) is **Paulo Moura's declarative object-
# oriented logic programming language** — a portable Prolog extension
# that adds Smalltalk-style classes, objects, and message passing on
# top of the underlying Prolog backend.  Logtalk has been in
# continuous development since 1998 (28 years) under a single
# maintainer (Paulo Moura) — one of the longest-running single-
# maintainer language projects active today.
#
# Logtalk's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. BACKEND-AGNOSTIC — Logtalk compiles to plain Prolog clauses
#      that run on any of 15 supported Prolog backends:
#         * B-Prolog       (commercial-academic)
#         * Ciao Prolog    (UPM Madrid)
#         * CxProlog       (academic)
#         * ECLiPSe        (cisco, used by Ericsson)
#         * GNU Prolog     (Daniel Diaz, GPL)
#         * GNU Prolog NC  (native-code compiler)
#         * JIProlog       (Java-hosted Prolog)
#         * XVM            (cross-platform virtual machine)
#         * SICStus        (commercial, SICS Sweden)
#         * SWI-Prolog     (CWI Amsterdam, MOST POPULAR)
#         * SWI-Prolog Pack (homemade pack)
#         * Tau Prolog     (JavaScript-hosted)
#         * Trealla Prolog (modern open-source)
#         * XSB            (Stony Brook tabling Prolog)
#         * YAP            (Yet Another Prolog)
#      This is UNPRECEDENTED portability: no other documented
#      language compiles to 15 different runtime targets.  Compare
#      Haskell (GHC + a few research backends), Scheme (MIT/CHICKEN/
#      Gambit/Racket/Guile — 5+ implementations), OCaml (ocaml +
#      js_of_ocaml + flambda), Java (multiple JVMs).  Logtalk's
#      backend list is the LONGEST of any documented declarative
#      language.
#
#   2. OBJECTS + CATEGORIES + PROTOCOLS — Logtalk has three first-
#      class entity types:
#         * `object`    — encapsulated namespace with state
#         * `category`  — fine-grained reusable mixin component
#         * `protocol`  — interface specification (predicate
#                         signatures only, no implementation)
#      An object can `implement` zero+ protocols and `import` zero+
#      categories, providing FINE-GRAINED composition.  Compare:
#         * Java:       class + interface + abstract class
#         * Smalltalk:  class + Trait (since Pharo 8)
#         * Rust:       struct + trait
#         * Ruby:       class + module
#      Logtalk's THREE-WAY entity decomposition is more granular
#      than any other documented language.  Categories specifically
#      address Logtalk's predecessor inheritance-only design's
#      well-known "fragile base class" problem.
#
#   3. PARAMETRIC OBJECTS — Logtalk objects can be parametric over
#      Prolog terms: `:- object(point(X, Y, Z)).` creates a family
#      of `point/3` objects keyed by their coordinates.  Sending a
#      message to `point(1,2,3)::distance(point(0,0,0), D)` invokes
#      the message on a specific parametric instance.  No other
#      documented OO language has Prolog-term-parametric objects
#      with unification-based dispatch.  Closest analog: Haskell's
#      type-parameterized newtype + type classes.  But Logtalk
#      dispatches via unification at runtime — first-class compile-
#      and-run-time polymorphism.
#
#   4. ISO-PROLOG SUBSET PORTABILITY — Logtalk source files can
#      contain plain ISO Prolog clauses inside `:- object(...)`
#      directives.  Every backend executes the same Logtalk source
#      code via a backend-specific adapter.  This means Logtalk
#      tooling (logtalk_tester, lgtdoc, logtalk_doclet) must
#      ABSTRACT OVER 15 PROLOG DIALECTS' different argv conventions,
#      different goal-evaluation flags, different module systems,
#      and different output formats.  No other documented testing
#      framework abstracts over so many runtime backends.
#
#   5. SELF-DOCUMENTING WITH lgtdoc — Logtalk includes a documentation
#      generator (`lgtdoc`) that reads Logtalk source files, extracts
#      `info/1`, `info/2`, `mode/2`, `parameters/2`, and `private/1`
#      directives, and emits XML/HTML/man-page/PDF documentation.
#      Compare doxygen (C++), godoc (Go), rustdoc (Rust), javadoc
#      (Java) — Logtalk's lgtdoc is the FIRST documented Prolog-
#      ecosystem documentation generator.
#
#   6. PROLOG-BACKEND-ABSTRACTION WITH ADAPTERS — Each Prolog backend
#      has a `.pl` adapter file in `adapters/` that abstracts over
#      its quirks (different module systems, different `current_op`
#      registries, different assertz/retract semantics).  When you
#      run `swilgt`, the adapter ensures the SAME Logtalk source
#      runs identically as when you run `gplgt`.  This is the
#      DECLARATIVE-LANGUAGE equivalent of LLVM's IR-to-many-backends
#      strategy but at the source-code level, not bytecode.
#
# Logtalk's relationship to other documented languages:
#
#   * Like Smalltalk        — objects + message passing
#   * Like Prolog (Picat,
#     PAKCS Curry-via-      — unification + clauses
#     Prolog backend)
#   * Like Java             — interface (protocol) + class (object)
#                             separation
#   * Like Eiffel           — design-by-contract via assertions
#   * Like Smalltalk Traits — categories as fine-grained mixin
#   * Unlike ALL of the above — combines Prolog's declarative
#     unification semantics with Smalltalk's object-message-passing
#     model into ONE language.  This combination is REFERRED TO IN
#     RESEARCH LITERATURE as "object-oriented logic programming"
#     (OOLP); Logtalk is the most-actively-developed OOLP language.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE logtalk_tester CLI — POSIX getopts + Bash Hand-Rolled Dispatcher
#
# logtalk_tester is a 1100-line bash script that:
#   1. Parses argv via `while getopts "vzp:o:m:f:d:t:j:n:s:b:u:c:l:e:g:r:i:wh"`
#   2. Validates the `-p` Prolog backend selection
#   3. Constructs a backend-specific Logtalk invocation command
#      (`bplgt -g`, `ciaolgt -e`, `cxlgt --goal`, etc.)
#   4. Recursively walks the directory tree looking for
#      `tester.lgt` / `tester.logtalk` files
#   5. For each tester file: launches the configured backend's
#      logtalk script with the test goal, captures output
#   6. Optionally runs jobs in parallel (`-j N`)
#   7. Aggregates results in the configured format
#   8. Emits coverage reports if `-c <format>` was set
#   9. Returns non-zero if any test failed/errored
#
# The argv parsing is POSIX-portable bash — the SAME getopts
# pattern that's been used since AT&T System V Release 3 in 1986
# (40 years).  Compare to clap/cobra/commander which are 5-15
# years old.  POSIX getopts is the SENIOR documented CLI library
# in the taxonomy by a margin of decades.
#
# Distinct from every other documented CLI library on FIVE specific
# axes:
#
#   1. POSIX SHELL BUILTIN — POSIX `getopts` is a shell BUILTIN, not
#      a library.  Every other documented CLI parser in the
#      taxonomy is a LIBRARY (linked / imported / required).  Bash,
#      ksh, zsh, dash, and every other POSIX-compliant shell ship
#      with `getopts` as a builtin command — no `import`, no `use`,
#      no Cargo.toml dependency.  FIRST documented CLI library that
#      is a SHELL BUILTIN.
#
#   2. SINGLE-LETTER-FLAGS-ONLY (NO LONG FLAGS) — POSIX getopts
#      ONLY parses `-x` short flags (with optional `value:` suffix
#      in the spec); GNU long-form `--xx-yy` flags are NOT supported
#      by POSIX getopts (you need `getopt(1)` for that, with
#      different semantics).  logtalk_tester uses 18 different
#      short flags (`v z p o m f d t j n s b u c l e g r i w h`) —
#      essentially exhausting the 26-letter alphabet.  FIRST
#      documented CLI library restricted to short-flag-only argv
#      conventions.
#
#   3. SPEC-STRING-BASED FLAG REGISTRATION — POSIX getopts
#      registers all flags via a SINGLE STRING (`"vzp:o:m:f:d:t:..."`)
#      where:
#         - Each letter is a recognized flag
#         - A letter followed by `:` means it takes a value
#         - The leading `:` (if present) means silent error mode
#      Compare clap's macro/derive registration, argparse's method
#      calls, cobra's struct fields.  POSIX getopts's spec-string
#      is the MOST COMPACT flag-registration format documented —
#      18 flags in 26 characters.
#
#   4. POSITIONAL-INDEX TRACKING VIA $OPTIND — Bash maintains a
#      magic global `$OPTIND` variable that tracks how far into
#      `$@` getopts has consumed.  After the parsing loop, the
#      script calls `shift $((OPTIND - 1))` to advance past
#      consumed flags and expose remaining positional args as
#      `"$@"`.  This is the canonical pattern for "flags then args"
#      shell scripts.  No other documented CLI library uses a magic
#      global integer for parser state.
#
#   5. NO BUILT-IN HELP/VERSION/SUBCOMMAND SUPPORT — POSIX getopts
#      does NOT auto-generate `-h`/`--help` output, does NOT
#      auto-generate `-V`/`--version` output, does NOT support
#      subcommand dispatch.  Authors hand-roll all of those.
#      logtalk_tester implements `-h` via a hand-rolled
#      `usage_help()` function that echoes 30+ lines of
#      formatted help text.  Compare clap's `#[command(version,
#      about)]` auto-magic.  FIRST documented CLI library with
#      ZERO meta-features (no help/version/subcommand built-ins).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/LogtalkDotOrg/logtalk3/blob/master/scripts/
# logtalk_tester.sh `usage_help()` function and `while getopts`
# parser.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '-p+[backend Prolog compiler]:backend:(b ciao cx eclipse gnu gnunc ji xvm sicstus swi swipack tau trealla xsb yap)' \
    '-o+[output verbosity]:output:(verbose minimal)' \
    '-m+[compilation mode]:mode:(optimal normal debug all)' \
    '-f+[test results format]:format:(default tap xunit xunit_net_v2 ctrf subunit_v1 subunit_v2)' \
    '-d+[directory to store test logs]:directory:_directories' \
    '-t+[timeout in seconds per test set]:seconds:' \
    '-j+[maximum number of concurrent test set processes]:jobs:' \
    '-n+[name of test driver and sourced files (minus extension)]:name:' \
    '-s+[suppress path prefix]:prefix:' \
    '-b+[bug report server (requires -u)]:tracker:(github gitlab)' \
    '-u+[base URL to generate links to test files]:url:' \
    '-c+[code coverage report format]:coverage:(none xml cobertura lcov)' \
    '-l+[directory-depth level to look for test sets (1 = current only)]:level:' \
    '-e+[exclude directories matching POSIX-extended regex]:regex:' \
    '-i+[integration-script command-line options]:options:' \
    '-g+[initialization goal]:goal:' \
    '-r+[random-generator starting seed]:seed:' \
    '-w[wipe default scratch directories before running each test set]' \
    '-z[audible completion notification (two chimes on 0, five otherwise)]' \
    '-v[print version of logtalk_tester]' \
    '-h[help]' \
    '*:arguments passed through to tests after --:' \
    && ret=0

return ret
